Headquartered in [Los Gatos, California](/Los_Gatos,_California), U.S., Netflix has carved out a territory that spans the globe, excepting only the usual suspects: [China](/China), [Crimea](/Crimea), [North Korea](/North_Korea), [Russia](/Russia), and [Syria](/Syria). &#91;3&#93; &#91;4&#93; It operates within the [entertainment](/Entertainment) and [mass media](/Mass_media) industries, offering [streaming media](/Streaming_media), [video on demand](/Video_on_demand), and [digital distribution](/Digital_distribution) as its core [products](/Product_(business)). Beyond mere distribution, Netflix has ventured into [film production](/Film_production), [film distribution](/film_distribution), [television production](/television_production), and [television distribution](/television_distribution), effectively becoming a vertically integrated content machine.

The company, [Netflix, Inc.](/Netflix,_Inc.), boasts a user base of 301.6 million as of January 21, 2025, &#91;5&#93; a number that’s frankly staggering. It launched its [DVD-by-mail](/DVD-by-mail) [movie rental](/Movie_rental) service on August 29, 1997, a quaint relic of a bygone era, before pivoting to its now-dominant [streaming media](/Streaming_media) service on January 16, 2007. In the intervening years, it has become the [most-subscribed video on demand](/List_of_streaming_media_services) [streaming media](/Streaming_media) service globally. By 2022, "Netflix Original" productions constituted half of its U.S. library, and the company even dipped its toes into [video game publishing](/Video_game_publishing) via [mobile games](/Mobile_game) on its flagship service. As of 2025, it ranks as the [18th most-visited website in the world](/List_of_most-visited_websites), a digital behemoth.

**History**

The narrative of Netflix is one of relentless adaptation, a survival story in the cutthroat digital age.

**Launch as a Mail-Based Rental Business (1997–2006)**

Netflix was born from the minds of [Marc Randolph](/Marc_Randolph) and [Reed Hastings](/Reed_Hastings) on August 29, 1997, in the sun-drenched cradle of [Scotts Valley, California](/Scotts_Valley,_California). Hastings, a man of numbers and logic, had just exited [Pure Software](/Pure_Software) after its acquisition for a cool $750 million, a substantial sum even by [Silicon Valley](/Silicon_Valley) standards. Randolph, already a seasoned entrepreneur with ventures like [MicroWarehouse](/MicroWarehouse) and a stint at [Borland](/Borland), found himself at Pure Atria after a company acquisition.

The spark for Netflix ignited during their shared commutes between [Santa Cruz, California](/Santa_Cruz,_California), and Pure Atria's headquarters. &#91;13&#93; Even [Patty McCord](/Patty_McCord), who would later shape Netflix's human resources, was privy to these discussions. &#91;14&#93; Randolph, ever the pragmatist, admired [Amazon](/Amazon_(company))'s model and sought a similar strategy for a large, portable consumer category – the internet. VHS tapes were considered, but their cost and fragility made them a non-starter. &#91;11&#93; The advent of the DVD, however, presented an opportunity. They tested the waters by mailing a [compact disc](/Compact_disc) to Hastings's home. Its safe arrival confirmed their hypothesis: a mail-order DVD rental service was viable. &#91;11&#93; Hastings, with his newfound capital from Pure Atria, invested $2.5 million, launching Netflix with 925 titles and 30 employees. &#91;13&#93; &#91;17&#93; &#91;18&#93; Their early ambition even caught the eye of [Jeff Bezos](/Jeff_Bezos), whose [Amazon](/Amazon_(company)) offered to acquire them for $14 to $16 million. Hastings, however, held the majority stake and, perhaps with a touch of foresight or stubbornness, declined. &#91;19&#93; &#91;20&#93;

Netflix's advantage lay in its ability to bypass the limitations of physical retail, offering a vast [long tail](/Long_tail) of titles. Early employee Cindy Holland colorfully described the company's acquisition of DVDs as "shoveling coal in the side door of the house." &#91;15&#93; While initially operating on a per-rental basis, Netflix introduced a monthly subscription in September 1999, ultimately abandoning the per-rental model by early 2000. This shift to a flat-fee, unlimited rental system, free of due dates and late fees, was revolutionary. The genius was that customers' homes became Netflix's warehouses, eliminating the need for costly storage and shipping. A clever, if slightly predatory, tactic involved secretly slowing deliveries to prolific users, the "pigs," to curb their voracious consumption. &#91;15&#93;

The company's trajectory was not without its turbulence. During the [dot-com bubble](/Dot-com_bubble), Netflix faced losses and a rejected offer to be acquired by Blockbuster for $50 million, a decision Blockbuster's CEO, [John Antioco](/John_Antioco), reportedly dismissed as a joke. &#91;23&#93; &#91;24&#93; The fallout from the bubble and the [September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks) forced Netflix to delay its [initial public offering](/Initial_public_offering) (IPO) and implement layoffs. &#91;25&#93;

The surge in DVD player popularity during the 2001 holiday season, however, propelled Netflix's subscriber growth. &#91;26&#93; The company went [public](/Public_company) in May 2002, trading on [NASDAQ](/NASDAQ). &#91;27&#93; By 2003, Netflix secured a patent for its subscription rental service, &#91;28&#93; and by 2004, it was profitable, a stark contrast to its earlier struggles. &#91;29&#93; In 2005, Netflix was shipping a staggering one million DVDs daily. &#91;30&#93;

Blockbuster's attempt to enter the DVD rental market in 2004, offering both online rentals and in-store returns, posed a challenge. &#91;31&#93; Despite its significant user base, Blockbuster's service ultimately couldn't stem the tide of Netflix's dominance. &#91;29&#93; The legal skirmishes were inevitable, with Netflix suing Blockbuster for [patent infringement](/Patent_infringement) in 2006, alleging that Blockbuster's online service copied Netflix's "dynamic queue" and subscription methods. &#91;32&#93; &#91;33&#93; The dispute was settled out of court in June 2007. &#91;34&#93; &#91;35&#93; &#91;36&#93; &#91;37&#93;

In a move that foreshadowed its future focus on algorithms, Netflix launched the [Netflix Prize](/Netflix_Prize) in October 2006, offering $1 million to anyone who could improve its recommendation engine, Cinematch, by more than 10%. &#91;38&#93; Cinematch, introduced in 2000, was designed to predict user preferences and introduce them to new content. &#91;39&#93; &#91;40&#93;

Through its division [Red Envelope Entertainment](/Red_Envelope_Entertainment), Netflix also engaged in licensing and distributing independent films. &#91;41&#93; However, this venture was closed in 2008, &#91;42&#93; &#91;43&#93; as the company's gaze shifted decisively towards streaming.

**Transition to Streaming Services (2007–2012)**

Hastings had always envisioned streaming as Netflix's ultimate destination, with the DVD service serving as a means to an end. &#91;15&#93; As internet speeds improved, the "Netflix box" concept—downloading movies overnight—was eventually scrapped in favor of a direct streaming model, inspired by the burgeoning popularity of platforms like [YouTube](/YouTube). &#91;44&#93; The streaming service launched in January 2007 with a modest library of 1,000 films, a stark contrast to its DVD catalog. &#91;45&#93; &#91;46&#93; Initially, it required [Internet Explorer](/Internet_Explorer) and was confined to computers, with Hollywood studios licensing their "second-run" content, seemingly unaware of the disruption they were enabling. &#91;15&#93; &#91;47&#93;

The billionth DVD was delivered in February 2007, &#91;48&#93; &#91;49&#93; while the development of a dedicated "Netflix Player" for televisions was entrusted to [Anthony Wood](/Anthony_Wood_(businessman)), founder of [ReplayTV](/ReplayTV). This project, however, ultimately evolved into the [Roku](/Roku) digital media player. &#91;50&#93; &#91;51&#93; &#91;52&#93; &#91;53&#93;

By January 2008, unlimited streaming was bundled with rental subscriptions, a strategic move to counter competitors like [Hulu](/Hulu) and [Apple](/Apple_Inc.). &#91;54&#93; &#91;55&#93; A significant technical setback occurred in August 2008 when a database corruption led Netflix to migrate its operations to [Amazon Web Services](/Amazon_Web_Services). &#91;56&#93; The company also began offering [Blu-ray](/Blu-ray) rentals and ceased selling used DVDs in November 2008. &#91;57&#93; By 2009, streaming traffic surpassed DVD shipments. &#91;58&#93;

Netflix entered into agreements with studios like [Warner Bros.](/Warner_Bros.), [Universal Pictures](/Universal_Pictures), and [20th Century Fox](/20th_Century_Fox) to delay new releases, a concession to bolster physical media sales. &#91;59&#93; &#91;60&#93; &#91;61&#93; Deals with [Relativity Media](/Relativity_Media) and a $1 billion pact with [Paramount](/Paramount_Pictures), [Lionsgate](/Lionsgate_Films), and [Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer](/Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer) further expanded its content library. &#91;62&#93; &#91;63&#93; Canada became Netflix's first international market in September 2010, &#91;64&#93; &#91;65&#93; followed by a standalone streaming service launch in November 2010. &#91;66&#93;

The acquisition of rights to [Breaking Bad](/Breaking_Bad) proved a pivotal moment, significantly boosting the show's viewership and cementing the "Netflix effect" where binge-watching fuels a show's popularity. &#91;67&#93; In 2011, Netflix solidified its presence by striking deals for branded [remote controls](/Remote_control) with device manufacturers. &#91;68&#93; By May 2011, it accounted for 30% of North American internet traffic during peak hours. &#91;69&#93; &#91;70&#93; &#91;71&#93; &#91;72&#93;

The controversial decision to separate its DVD and streaming services under the Qwikster brand in 2011 backfired spectacularly, leading to customer backlash and a stock price plummet. &#91;73&#93; &#91;74&#93; &#91;75&#93; &#91;76&#93; &#91;77&#93; &#91;78&#93; &#91;79&#93; &#91;80&#93; &#91;81&#93; &#91;82&#93; &#91;83&#93; The company quickly reversed course, apologizing and retaining its integrated service. &#91;84&#93; &#91;85&#93; &#91;86&#93;

Netflix continued its European expansion, launching in the UK and Ireland in January 2012, &#91;89&#93; and securing deals with [The Weinstein Company](/The_Weinstein_Company) &#91;90&#93; &#91;91&#93; and [DreamWorks Animation](/DreamWorks_Animation). &#91;87&#93; The acquisition of DVD.com in March 2012 &#91;92&#93; was a subtle nod to its roots, even as its future lay in the digital realm. &#91;93&#93; &#91;94&#93; In April 2012, Netflix formed a [political action committee](/Political_action_committee), FLIXPAC, to engage in policy debates, particularly concerning [net neutrality](/Network_neutrality). &#91;95&#93; &#91;96&#93; &#91;97&#93; Deals with [Open Road Films](/Open_Road_Films) &#91;98&#93; &#91;99&#93; and [Epix](/Epix) &#91;102&#93; &#91;103&#93; &#91;104&#93; further bolstered its content pipeline. The landmark deal with Disney in December 2012 secured exclusive rights to its animated and live-action films, &#91;107&#93; &#91;108&#93; &#91;109&#93; marking a significant coup. Content deals with [Turner Broadcasting System](/Turner_Broadcasting_System) and [Warner Bros. Television](/Warner_Bros._Television) followed in January 2013, filling the void left by expiring [Viacom](/Viacom_(2005%E2%80%932019)) deals. &#91;110&#93; Limited expansion in 2013, with the Netherlands being the sole addition, indicated a strategic pause. &#91;111&#93; &#91;112&#93; &#91;113&#93;

**Development of Original Programming and Distribution Expansion (2013–2017)**

Netflix's deep dive into original programming was a calculated gamble, fueled by its unparalleled data on viewer behavior. &#91;15&#93; The commissioning of [House of Cards](/House_of_Cards_(American_TV_series)) in March 2011, outbidding traditional networks, was a watershed moment, marking the first instance of a streaming service producing a first-run television series. &#91;114&#93; The simultaneous release of its entire first season, catering to the binge-watching phenomenon, was equally revolutionary. &#91;15&#93; The subsequent additions of [Orange Is the New Black](/Orange_Is_the_New_Black) and the revival of [Arrested Development](/Arrested_Development) solidified Netflix's position as a content powerhouse. &#91;115&#93; &#91;116&#93; The acquisition of the Norwegian drama [Lilyhammer](/Lilyhammer) further demonstrated its commitment to international content and its willingness to break from traditional release models. &#91;117&#93; &#91;118&#93;

[House of Cards](/House_of_Cards_(American_TV_series)) debuted in February 2013 as the first "Netflix Original," &#91;119&#93; followed by children's series based on [DreamWorks Animation](/DreamWorks_Animation) properties like [Turbo: F.A.S.T.](/Turbo_Fast). &#91;120&#93; &#91;121&#93; [Orange is the New Black](/Orange_Is_the_New_Black) premiered in July 2013, quickly becoming Netflix's most-watched original series to date. &#91;122&#93; &#91;123&#93; The introduction of a [Facebook](/Facebook) sharing feature in March 2013, enabled by modifications to the [Video Privacy Protection Act](/Video_Privacy_Protection_Act), &#91;124&#93; &#91;125&#93; and the reintroduction of user "Profiles" in August 2013, &#91;126&#93; &#91;127&#93; &#91;128&#93; &#91;129&#93; further enhanced user engagement.

The ambitious slate of [Marvel Television](/Marvel_Television) series—[Daredevil](/Daredevil_(Marvel_Comics_character)), [Jessica Jones](/Jessica_Jones), [Iron Fist](/Iron_Fist_(character)), and [Luke Cage](/Luke_Cage)—along with the miniseries [The Defenders](/Defenders_(comics)), marked a significant expansion into superhero storytelling. &#91;130&#93; &#91;131&#93; &#91;132&#93; &#91;133&#93; &#91;134&#93; Disney's subsequent content agreements, including the acquisition of animated [Star Wars](/Star_Wars) series like [Star Wars: The Clone Wars](/Star_Wars:_The_Clone_Wars_(2008_TV_series)), underscored the evolving landscape of content licensing. &#91;135&#93;

Netflix's iconic [audio logo](/Audio_logo), first introduced in 2014, became an auditory signature of its brand.

The company's proactive approach to infrastructure saw it striking deals with internet service providers like [Comcast](/Comcast) to improve streaming quality. &#91;136&#93; &#91;137&#93; &#91;138&#93; A multi-year deal with [Arrested Development](/Arrested_Development) creator [Mitchell Hurwitz](/Mitchell_Hurwitz) &#91;139&#93; and a major film partnership with [Sony Pictures Animation](/Sony_Pictures_Animation) &#91;140&#93; were followed by a logo redesign. &#91;141&#93;

International expansion continued with launches in six European markets in September 2014, &#91;142&#93; and participation in [Internet Slowdown Day](/Internet_Slowdown_Day) to advocate for [net neutrality](/Net_neutrality). &#91;143&#93; A lucrative deal with [Adam Sandler](/Adam_Sandler) and [Happy Madison Productions](/Happy_Madison_Productions) in October 2014 demonstrated its strategy of investing in established talent. &#91;144&#93;

Netflix's commitment to accessibility was evident in its introduction of [audio description](/Audio_description) in April 2015, &#91;145&#93; &#91;146&#93; and its subsequent settlement with the [American Council of the Blind](/American_Council_of_the_Blind) to ensure timely descriptions. &#91;147&#93; The service expanded to [Australia](/Australia) and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) in March 2015, &#91;148&#93; &#91;149&#93; followed by Japan in September &#91;150&#93; &#91;151&#93; &#91;152&#93; and Italy, Portugal, and Spain in October. &#91;153&#93;

The ambitious global rollout in January 2016, encompassing 130 additional countries, &#91;154&#93; including significant investment in African content and storytelling, &#91;155&#93; &#91;156&#93; showcased its worldwide aspirations. Netflix Studios expanded its production capabilities, &#91;157&#93; while the simple speed-test website Fast.com offered a no-frills utility. &#91;158&#93; &#91;159&#93; &#91;160&#93; &#91;161&#93; The introduction of offline playback in November 2016 &#91;162&#93; &#91;163&#93; &#91;164&#93; &#91;165&#93; and the release of an estimated 30 original series and films in 2016 alone, &#91;166&#93; highlighted its prolific output.

A music publishing deal with [BMG Rights Management](/BMG_Rights_Management) in February 2017 &#91;167&#93; and a licensing agreement with China's iQIYI &#91;168&#93; &#91;169&#93; signaled its engagement with diverse international markets. The acquisition of [Millarworld](/Millarworld) in August 2017 marked Netflix's first corporate acquisition. &#91;170&#93; A significant development deal with [Shonda Rhimes](/Shonda_Rhimes) and [Shondaland](/Shondaland) &#91;171&#93; further bolstered its roster of high-profile creators. Efforts to improve in-flight Wi-Fi for passengers underscored its pervasive integration into modern life. &#91;172&#93; A $500 million investment in Canadian content, &#91;173&#93; &#91;174&#93; &#91;175&#93; and the ambitious goal of having original content comprise half its library by 2019, with an $8 billion investment planned for 2018, &#91;176&#93; demonstrated its commitment to original programming. The "Skip Intro" feature, introduced in October 2017, &#91;177&#93; &#91;178&#93; was a subtle but appreciated nod to viewer convenience. Deals with creators like [Jenji Kohan](/Jenji_Kohan) &#91;179&#93; and the company's withdrawal from a Golden Globe party with [The Weinstein Company](/The_Weinstein_Company) amid sexual abuse allegations &#91;180&#93; reflected the industry's evolving ethical landscape.

**Expansion into International Productions and New Productions (2017–2020)**

Netflix's commitment to global storytelling intensified with the announcement of its first original Colombian series in November 2017, &#91;181&#93; and a significant deal with [Shawn Levy](/Shawn_Levy) and [21 Laps Entertainment](/21_Laps_Entertainment). &#91;182&#93; The company also made substantial investments in stand-up comedy specials from prominent comedians. &#91;183&#93;

The acquisition of [The Cloverfield Paradox](/The_Cloverfield_Paradox) from [Paramount Pictures](/Paramount_Pictures) for $50 million and its surprise release during [Super Bowl LII](/Super_Bowl_LII) highlighted Netflix's agile and unconventional distribution strategies. &#91;184&#93; &#91;185&#93; Further acquisitions of international distribution rights for films like [Annihilation](/Annihilation_(film)) and [News of the World](/News_of_the_World_(film)), &#91;185&#93; &#91;186&#93; along with worldwide distribution of [Extinction](/Extinction_(2018_film)), [Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle](/Mowgli:_Legend_of_the_Jungle), &#91;187&#93; [The Lovebirds](/The_Lovebirds_(2020_film)), &#91;188&#93; and [The Woman in the Window](/The_Woman_in_the_Window_(2021_film)) &#91;189&#93; demonstrated its global reach. The docuseries [Formula 1: Drive to Survive](/Formula_1:_Drive_to_Survive) offered an inside look at the world of motorsports, &#91;190&#93; while integration with [Sky UK](/Sky_UK) provided a seamless viewing experience for its subscribers. &#91;191&#93;

Netflix's withdrawal from the [Cannes Film Festival](/Cannes_Film_Festival) in April 2018, in protest of new rules requiring theatrical releases for competition films, underscored the ongoing tension between streaming and traditional cinema. &#91;193&#93; &#91;194&#93; &#91;195&#93; The company's strategic expansion into non-traditional foreign markets, evidenced by successful shows like [Dark](/Dark_(TV_series)) from Germany, [Ingobernable](/Ingobernable) from [Mexico](/Mexico), and [3%](/3%25) from [Brazil](/Brazil), reflected its global content strategy. &#91;196&#93; &#91;197&#93; &#91;198&#93;

The landmark deal with former President [Barack Obama](/Barack_Obama) and [Michelle Obama](/Michelle_Obama) in May 2018, to produce content through their [Higher Ground Productions](/Higher_Ground_Productions), was a significant cultural and strategic coup. &#91;199&#93; &#91;200&#93; The partnership with [Telltale Games](/Telltale_Games) to port adventure games to the service in a streaming format &#91;201&#93; &#91;202&#93; marked its foray into interactive entertainment, with [Minecraft: Story Mode](/Minecraft:_Story_Mode) being the first release. &#91;203&#93; Netflix's leading position in Emmy nominations in July 2018 &#91;204&#93; and overall deals with acclaimed creators like [Harlan Coben](/Harlan_Coben) &#91;205&#93; and [Alex Hirsch](/Alex_Hirsch) &#91;206&#93; cemented its reputation as a premier content destination. The acquisition of [Albuquerque Studios](/Albuquerque_Studios) &#91;207&#93; and a multi-picture deal with [Paramount Pictures](/Paramount_Pictures) &#91;208&#93; further expanded its production infrastructure. The documentary series [The Last Dance](/The_Last_Dance_(miniseries)) chronicling Michael Jordan and the [1997–98 Chicago Bulls season](/1997%E2%80%9398_Chicago_Bulls_season) garnered widespread acclaim. &#91;210&#93; &#91;211&#93;

The debut of [Sex Education](/Sex_Education_(TV_series)) in January 2019 garnered critical acclaim. &#91;212&#93; Netflix's membership in the [Motion Picture Association of America](/Motion_Picture_Association_of_America) &#91;213&#93; and overall deals with creators like [Mike Flanagan](/Mike_Flanagan_(filmmaker)) &#91;214&#93; and [Dark Horse Entertainment](/Dark_Horse_Entertainment) &#91;215&#93; underscored its deepening commitment to original content. The opening of a hub at [Shepperton Studios](/Shepperton_Studios) &#91;216&#93; and exclusive deals with [David Benioff](/David_Benioff) and [D.B. Weiss](/D.B._Weiss) &#91;217&#93; &#91;218&#93; &#91;219&#93; &#91;220&#93; &#91;221&#93; demonstrated its strategy of securing top creative talent. The adaptation of [Liu Cixin](/Liu_Cixin)'s [The Three-Body Problem](/The_Three-Body_Problem_(novel)) &#91;222&#93; and a deal with [The Duffer Brothers](/The_Duffer_Brothers) for future projects &#91;223&#93; signaled its continued investment in ambitious storytelling.

The multi-year agreement with [Nickelodeon](/Nickelodeon) to produce animated films and series based on its library, including projects related to [SpongeBob SquarePants](/SpongeBob_SquarePants), &#91;224&#93; &#91;225&#93; &#91;226&#93; and the termination of its deal with Disney due to the launch of [Disney+](/Disney%2B) &#91;227&#93; &#91;228&#93; marked significant shifts in content strategy. The company's efforts to preserve the Paris Theatre in [Manhattan](/Manhattan) &#91;229&#93; &#91;230&#93; &#91;231&#93; highlighted its appreciation for cinematic heritage.

**Expansion into Gaming, Squid Game, New Programming, and New Initiatives (2021–2022)**

Netflix's dominance in awards season continued in 2021, with a leading number of Academy Award and Emmy nominations and wins, showcasing its critical acclaim. &#91;246&#93; &#91;247&#93; A groundbreaking film licensing deal with [Sony Pictures Entertainment](/Sony_Pictures_Entertainment) &#91;248&#93; &#91;249&#93; &#91;250&#93; and the opening of its first Canadian headquarters in [Toronto](/Toronto), along with new offices in Sweden, [Rome](/Rome), and [Istanbul](/Istanbul), &#91;251&#93; &#91;252&#93; demonstrated its commitment to global expansion. The inaugural "Geeked Week" virtual event &#91;253&#93; and first-look deals with prominent creators like [Jennifer Lopez](/Jennifer_Lopez) &#91;254&#93; and [Steven Spielberg](/Steven_Spielberg) &#91;257&#93; &#91;258&#93; solidified its position as a premier content platform. The launch of an online store for branded merchandise &#91;255&#93; &#91;256&#93; and a first-look deal with animation studio [Powerhouse Animation Studios](/Powerhouse_Animation_Studios) &#91;259&#93; further diversified its business model.

Netflix's strategic entry into video games, with the hiring of [Mike Verdu](/Mike_Verdu) and plans to launch [mobile games](/Mobile_gaming) by 2022, &#91;260&#93; &#91;261&#93; represented a bold new frontier. Early trial offerings in Poland and subsequent global launches on Android and iOS devices &#91;262&#93; showcased its ambition in this space. First-look deals with talent like [Joey King](/Joey_King) &#91;263&#93; and [Zack Snyder](/Zack_Snyder) &#91;264&#93; &#91;265&#93; &#91;266&#93; &#91;267&#93; &#91;268&#93; &#91;269&#93; demonstrated its continued investment in high-profile partnerships. The company's original programming constituted 40% of its U.S. library by August 2021, &#91;270&#93; and the "TUDUM" fan event garnered significant viewership. &#91;271&#93; &#91;272&#93; &#91;273&#93; Experiential events like "The Queen's Ball: A Bridgerton Experience" &#91;274&#93; and the phenomenal success of [Squid Game](/Squid_Game) &#91;198&#93; &#91;275&#93; underscored its cultural impact. Acquisitions of [Millarworld](/Millarworld) &#91;170&#93; and [Roald Dahl Story Company](/Roald_Dahl) &#91;277&#93; &#91;278&#93; &#91;279&#93; &#91;280&#93; and game developer [Night School Studio](/Night_School_Studio) &#91;281&#93; demonstrated a strategic expansion into intellectual property and interactive entertainment. The Netflix Book Club and partnerships with [Starbucks](/Starbucks) &#91;282&#93; &#91;283&#93; &#91;284&#93; and the shift in viewership metrics to hours watched &#91;285&#93; reflected its evolving business strategies. The launch of mobile games in November 2021 &#91;286&#93; &#91;287&#93; and the "Top10 on Netflix.com" website &#91;289&#93; were further steps in its digital evolution. The acquisition of visual effects company [Scanline VFX](/Scanline_VFX) &#91;290&#93; and partnership deals with creators like [Roberto Patino](/Roberto_Patino) &#91;291&#93; and [Kalinda Vazquez](/Kalinda_Vazquez) &#91;296&#93; showcased its continued investment in production capabilities and creative talent. Partnerships with organizations like IllumiNative &#91;293&#93; &#91;294&#93; and the launch of the "Tudum" companion website &#91;295&#93; further solidified its brand presence. Commitments to invest in original French content, &#91;298&#93; &#91;299&#93; and expansion into sports docuseries like those following [PGA Tour](/PGA_Tour) golfers and professional tennis players, &#91;300&#93; &#91;301&#93; demonstrated its diversification strategy. Acquisitions of game developers Next Games &#91;302&#93; and [Boss Fight Entertainment](/Boss_Fight_Entertainment) &#91;303&#93;, along with new offices in [Poland](/Poland) &#91;306&#93; and lease extensions in [Vancouver, Canada](/Vancouver), &#91;307&#93; underscored its global operational growth. The company's suspension of operations in Russia &#91;309&#93; and refusal to comply with [Roskomnadzor](/Roskomnadzor) directives &#91;310&#93; highlighted its stance on geopolitical issues. The acknowledgment of widespread password sharing and subsequent layoffs &#91;313&#93; &#91;314&#93; &#91;315&#93; &#91;316&#93; &#91;317&#93; &#91;318&#93; &#91;319&#93; &#91;320&#93; &#91;321&#93; signaled a period of recalibration. Partnerships with [Ryan Reynolds](/Ryan_Reynolds) and [Blake Lively](/Blake_Lively) &#91;323&#93; and the Arab Fund For Arts And Culture &#91;324&#93; demonstrated its commitment to supporting diverse talent. The launch of an [Exploding Kittens](/Exploding_Kittens) mobile game &#91;325&#93; and deals with creators like [J. Miles Dale](/J._Miles_Dale) &#91;326&#93; and [Studio Colorido](/Studio_Colorido) &#91;327&#93; showcased its continued expansion into new content formats and collaborations. The success of [Stranger Things 4](/Stranger_Things_season_4) and its record-breaking viewership &#91;330&#93; &#91;332&#93; and the acquisition of animation studio [Animal Logic](/Animal_Logic) &#91;333&#93; &#91;334&#93; cemented its position as a dominant force in entertainment